I found it thanks to [@Alexey-yakunin][1] :)

When you working with ActiveMQ , If your destination is &quot;queue&quot; then the speed of producing messages to 
the queue is way more slower than consuming from the queue. 
It&#39;s because, like the way [@Alexey-yakunin][1] said &quot;when you send messages to the ActiveMQ queue, you put them in the database. The database is located on your hard drive (bottleneck). Reading from a database is faster than writing to it&quot;.

So to prove this theory, I did this test: 

(Instead of sending messages to ```queue``` I sent them to ```topic``` without any durable subscribers)

```No durable subscribers to the topic == No databse ```
```
        from(&quot;file:G:/highlight&quot;).to(&quot;activemq:topic:newVersion&quot;);
        from(&quot;activemq:topic:newVersion&quot;).process(new Processor() {
            @Override
            public void process(Exchange exchange) throws Exception {
                long time = System.currentTimeMillis();
                Date date = new Date(time);
                System.out.println(date);
                
            }
        });
```
For ```2000 messages```, It took only ```3 seconds``` to produce and consume all the messages. 

Also These are options that I set in spring boot ```application.properties``` in order to get most out of activemq: 

```
camel.component.activemq.broker-u-r-l=tcp://localhost:61616

// By default it is set to false so make sure you set this to true
camel.component.activemq.use-pooled-connection=true 

camel.component.activemq.transacted=false

//Remember, the messages will be lost if the broker crashes or is restarted.
camel.component.activemq.delivery-persistent=false

camel.component.activemq.wait-for-provision-correlation-to-be-updated-thread-sleeping-time=50
```
